{
  "doc_id": "46345",
  "text": "Adenosine, a purine nucleoside, plays an important role in the human body. It is produced constitutively by cells under normal conditions, and its concentration increases under metabolic stress (e.g. ischemia) or at sites of tissue injury [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] . In mammalian cells, adenosine can be carried across cell membranes by the concentrative nucleoside transporters (also known as SLC28 family proteins) and the equilibrative nucleoside transporters (ENTs; 4 also known as SLC29 proteins) [CITATION_4] . There are four known ENTs, designated ENT1, ENT2, ENT3, and ENT4. All four isoforms are widely distributed in mammalian tissues. The best characterized members of the family, ENT1 and ENT2, appear to function primarily at the cell surface [CITATION_5] . In contrast, ENT3 (6 -8) and ENT4 [CITATION_6] are predominantly expressed in intracellular membranes [CITATION_7] . Uniquely, ENT3 is pH-sensitive and optimally active under acidic conditions (optimal pH value of 5.5), probably reflecting the subcellular location of the transporters in acidic compartments, like lysosomes [CITATION_8] [CITATION_9] . In addition, adenosine can be broken down by adenosine deaminase (ADA).",
